SIMPLE: entwine
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Entwine
<hw>En*twine"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[Pref.
<ets>en-</ets> + <ets>twine</ets>. Cf. <er>Intwine</er>.]</ety> <def>To
twine, twist, or wreathe together or round.</def> <altsp>[Written also
<asp>intwine</asp>.]</altsp>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Entwined</qex> in duskier wreaths her braided locks.</q>
<rj><qau>Shelley.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thy glorious household stuff did me <qex>entwine</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Herbert.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Entwine</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Entwine
<hw>En*twine"</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To be twisted or
twined.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>With whose imperial laurels might <qex>entwine</qex> no
cypress.</q> <rj><qau>De Quincey.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Entwinement</ent>⟦br⟧
